<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Low counter seen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The possibility of a counter bid for Scottish supermarket chain William Low
sent the shares powering ahead 17 to 253p, well above the 225p a share
agreed offer made by Tesco the previous day.
Most of the support reflected the surprise announcement by J. Sainsbury that
it was considering its options. But the market was also scratching around
for other possible candidates. There was a feeling that some overseas groups
might grab at the chance to grab Low's 6.6 per cent of Scottish market
share. Two names that attracted some consideration were Rewe, one of
Germany's largest food retailers and Dairy Farm International, the food
retailing arm of Hong Kong's Jardine Matheson. The pressure on the bidder
and potential bidder saw Tesco restrained to a rise of only a half to 233p
and Sainsbury fall 2 1/2 to 397p.
</TEXT>
