FT  16 JUL 94 / International Company News: Computer havoc on Nasdaq system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Computer problems created havoc for US traders and investors using the
screen-based Nasdaq stock trading system yesterday, as the opening of the
country's second largest stock market was delayed for two and a half hours
while systems experts tried to find the fault, writes Patrick Harverson in
New York
Although the Nasdaq market, which is run by the National Association of
Securities Dealers and handles up to 263m shares a day worth billions of
dollars, finally opened just before noon, many parts of the system remained
closed all day, costing millions of dollars in lost business.
