<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 94 / Tory MP in sacking row with whips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was last night embroiled in a dispute with a ministerial aide
who said that whips had lied when they said he was sacked, just days before
the cabinet reshuffle.
Mr Tim Devlin yesterday insisted that he resigned - in spite of attempts by
ministers and whips to persuade him to stay on - in protest against planned
defence cuts in his Stockton South constituency.
When Mr Devlin, the parliamentary private secretary to Sir Nicholas Lyell,
the attorney general, said he had resigned he was immediately contradicted
by Conservative party managers. They took the unprecedented step of saying
that he had been dismissed for his 'poor voting record and general
ineffectiveness'.
Friends of Mr Devlin asked why the whips should sack a ministerial aide when
they could remove him from office quietly next week. Last night Mrs Marjorie
Simpson, chair of the Stockton South constituency party, said she believed
the whips were lying and backed Mr Devlin.
The whips' office said Mr Devlin was sacked after he missed four important
Commons votes. They said Mr Devlin's dismissal was connected solely with
party discipline.
Party managers said that with a majority of 15 they were not prepared to
allow members of government to 'cherry pick' which votes they were prepared
to attend. The whips said the attorney general had been kept informed of Mr
Devlin's dismissal and had accepted their judgment. Sir Nicholas's office
would not comment.
Last night Mr Devlin - who has the reputation of being a rebel within
government - said on BBC radio: 'I am staggered. The chief whip and the
deputy chief whip Greg Knight and the attorney general have been trying all
week to stop me from resigning. It has been rumoured in the press for a few
days that I was going to resign. But they announce I am sacked. I find that
unbelievable.'
Asked whether the whips had been lying, Mr Devlin responded: 'Yes.'
Mr Devlin said Sir Nicholas had tried to persuade him to remain and fight
his corner in the government. But he felt unable to do so once the defence
white paper had revealed the loss of 384 jobs in his constituency.
Mr Devlin's removal gave rise to speculation that Sir Nicholas might be
dropped from the government in next week's reshuffle. The rumours were
fuelled by the announcement that Mr Devlin's duties were to be carried out
by Mr Gary Streeter, Tory MP for Plymouth Sutton, who will remain PPS to Sir
Derek Spencer, the solicitor general.
Party managers denied that the affair would have any effect on Sir
Nicholas's future.
Mr Devlin has featured in newspaper reports about his lobbying for the
release from prison of a man charged in connection with drugs dealing and
who was also alleged to have been a police informer. The man left the
country after charges were dropped.
While the matter was an embarrassment to the attorney general, government
advisers made it clear that it had nothing to do with Mr Devlin's return to
the backbenches.
</TEXT>
