<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 94 / Tories improve party finances
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservative party achieved an operating surplus of more than Pounds 2m
 -the largest in its history - according to the party's report and accounts
published yesterday.
But the balance sheet shows the Tories still have a bank overdraft of Pounds
15.82m.
Sir Norman Fowler, the party's out-going chairman, was upbeat about the
turnaround of a net operating deficit last year of Pounds 2.19m to a surplus
of Pounds 2.06m.
He said: 'The most encouraging feature of the year has been the recovery in
the finances of the party. After three successive years of deficits of
around Pounds 5m, the position was improved in 1992-93 when losses were more
than halved. Now in 1993-94 we have achieved a surplus of more than Pounds
2m.
'This represents the largest surplus in the party's history - a vital and
encouraging first step towards the elimination of the still substantial
overall deficit.'
</TEXT>
