<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 94 / US bonds limit rise for dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The dollar continued its cautious recovery on the London foreign exchange
market yesterday, although it eased slightly against the yen in New York
last night under pressure from weaker US bond prices.
Earlier in the week, the US currency had fallen to fresh lows against both
the yen and the D-Mark after last weekend's decision by the Group of Seven
leading industrial nations not to announce any programme of dollar support.
The improved inflationary outlook in the US, which supported the bond market
on Thursday and early yesterday, spread to the UK, where the Bank of England
announced a long-dated conventional gilt auction after a period of shorter
term, non-conventional funding.
Share prices in the UK were also firmer, with the FT-SE 100 index closing
24.4 points higher at 3,074.8, bringing the total gain for the week to 112.4
points.
After closing in London nearly a pfennig firmer in London against the D-Mark
at DM1.5558, the dollar held its ground in New York trading, where it stood
at DM1.5531 last night. Against the yen, however, the dollar fell in London
to Y97.9050, and eased further to Y97.75 later in New York after a modest
retreat in bond prices. Analysts were sceptical yesterday, though, about
whether the US currency was experiencing anything more than a temporary
correction.
Investor sentiment towards the currency remains bearish.
Editorial Comment, Page 8
Currencies, Page 13; London stocks, Page 15; World stocks, Page 21 and
Weekend II
