<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (32): PostScript
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fading short-term fortunes are visible pretty well across the whole range of
unit trusts and investment trusts. With markets around the globe turning
dreary to poor in the second quarter of the year, it is very hard to find
unit trusts that have achieved a return of 30 per cent over a year.
Our list three months ago contained dozens of such funds, especially in the
Far East and continental Europe. This time there are only six or seven, led
by Providence Capitol European with an impressive 48.5 per cent.
The much more typical picture is that of a fund which has shown a slightly
negative return over 12 months. All the sector averages for the UK and North
America are in this position - although this is a harsh test, because the
one-year figures bear the full burden of the gap between bid and offer
prices (usually about 6 per cent).
The outlook for the short-term performance numbers during the remainder of
1994 remains poor, because most stock markets around the world were rising
strongly during the third and fourth quarters of 1993. Unless unit prices
make very good progress from here, they will be slipping further and further
behind their year-earlier values.
Does it matter? Not in the sense that unit trusts (and investment trusts,
too) should normally be regarded as long-term investments. Over periods like
five years (and certainly over 10 years) nearly all funds are showing decent
profits.
But short-term timing can still be important. Last year was the biggest year
ever for net sales of unit trusts to investors, at Pounds 9.1bn, and there
was a surge of new investment trust issues, too, amounting to Pounds 3bn.
Most of the money that went in during 1993, certainly in the later months,
is likely to show a loss over one year.
Investors who subscribed back in 1992 did a great deal better. The average
unit trust returned about 27 per cent during 1993. The trouble is, only
Pounds 0.7bn was invested in unit trusts in 1992, a particularly poor year
for sales.
The old problem of feast and famine is being seen again. Investors dither
when the stock market is cheap, and are then lured in near the top. Another
generation of investors becomes disappointed.
The one-year investment trust figures are looking healthier than the unit
trust equivalents, with most sectors showing a positive return of 10 per
cent or so. However, the figures strictly speaking ought to be reduced by 3
or 4 per cent, reflecting initial dealing costs and spreads, to make them
comparable with the unit trust performance.
Meanwhile pressure from the continuing wave of new investment trust issues,
which has pulled in another Pounds 3bn in just the past six months, is
beginning to weaken the average discount to asset value for the sector,
though the damage has been modest so far.
Private investors, in fact, have still been buying collective funds on quite
a heavy scale in recent months, and the causes of the weakness in stock
markets have originated elsewhere, in the gyrations of international bond
markets.
If savers are learning the lesson that it is better to buy into weakness
rather than into a heady bull market, then they may improve their long-term
results.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
