<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (29): Investors take
a longer view - Unit trusts / Sales figures suggest a healthier attitude on
the part of savers, as competition grows to offer them more attractive
charging structures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Traditionally, the period after the end of the tax year is a relatively
quiet one for unit trusts.
Most unit trusts bought by private investors are in the form of a personal
equity plan (Pep) and, since the rush to use up annual limits tends to be
confined to the end of the tax year, that is the time when unit trusts sales
also tend to be highest.
Sales have fallen off since March when net investment in unit trusts topped
Pounds 1.37bn, making it the best March figure on record, but subsequent
investment has still been sizeable, dropping only to Pounds 976m in April
and to Pounds 726.4m in May.
Philip Warland, director-general of the Association of Unit Trusts and
Investment Funds, said the figures indicated a healthy change in saving
habits, as investors appeared to be ignoring short-term market movements and
investing for the long term.
Last year was a record for the unit trust industry, helped by prevailing low
interest rates, with net inflows of Pounds 9.1bn. Net investment of Pounds
4.2bn in the first five months of this year was still strong, despite - or
possibly because of - the dip in the UK market since February.
With sales still buoyant, competition continues apace, with the main
emphasis on charging structures and on dressing up an existing product to
sustain the interest of potential investors.
At the end of June, Fidelity packaged its existing Peps into a mortgage to
launch Fidelity Pep Mortgage Plan. Borrowers can either use a Fidelity Pep -
the company recommends three in particular - to bolt on to an interest-only
mortgage secured from one of 40 lenders who have said they will sell the
Pep; or they can choose Fidelity's package, with Bank of Ireland providing
the mortgage and Zurich Life the term assurance.
At the same time, Fidelity has changed the charging structure of its Peps by
lifting the three-year exit fees, from July 4, but by pushing up the initial
charge from 2 per cent to 3 per cent from August 1.
When it pioneered the introduction of withdrawal fees on unit trust Peps, in
June 1992, and cut the initial charge from 5.25 to 2 per cent, it said it
wanted to avoid diluting the tax benefits of a Pep with a high initial
charge.
Other companies followed, including Gartmore, Guinness Flight, Scottish
Equitable and, most recently M&amp;G, which on January 1 abolished the initial
charge on its Managed Income Pep, but introduced five-year withdrawal
charges.
Gartmore has also lifted withdrawal charges on its unit trust Peps and
raised its initial charge from 2 to 3 per cent. The two gave the same reason
for the move: investors found the dual charging structure 'confusing.'
Fidelity also said that it did not want any penalties attached to the new
mortgage package; but both companies have also found that few investors have
been cashing in their Pep early.
Others may follow, although M&amp;G says that it has no intention of abolishing
withdrawal charges on the Managed Income Pep, and may indeed extend the
charging structure to other Peps. It says it has not found customer
confusion, but attributes this to the lack of an initial charge. M&amp;G's
Rachel Medill said: 'There is only one set of charges, so for us it is a
simple message. Two sets of charges may give investors the impression that
they are being charged twice.'
Fidelity's and Gartmore's 3 per cent initial charge is still competitive
compared with the industry average of 5.25 to 6 per cent, but it is confined
to unit trust Peps. Murray Johnstone's initial charge on its unit trusts is
1 per cent, and Lazard has not levied an initial charge on its unit trusts
since 1988. At the beginning of May, Invesco cut the initial charge across
the range of its unit trusts to 3 per cent.
Alan Wren, managing director of Invesco fund managers, made no secret that
the idea was to increase greater market share and attract longer-term
investors after two years of stagnation at Invesco, where funds under
management had not increased despite a market average growth of between 50
per cent and 100 per cent.
Although initial and annual charges are one factor in any decision to buy a
unit trust, performance is far more important in the long run. Here, Invesco
is on weak territory and says that one of its tasks is to improve
performance. With the exception of its Japan Smaller Companies fund, which
has a good record, many of its UK funds are to be found in the lower half of
the performance tables.
MORE MANAGERS PLAN TO EXPLORE EMERGING MARKETS
The Far East and emerging markets have been the main geographical areas
acting as a spur to new launches.
Hypo F&amp;C hopes to capitalise on future growth in the Japanese market with
its Japanese Growth fund, while Exeter Fund managers is using closed-end
funds to invest in the Far East through its Pacific Growth fund.
Save &amp; Prosper has turned its attentions away from the Far East to South
America with its Latin America Fund. Portfolio's Emerging Markets Fund aims
to take the pick of emerging market unit trusts through a fund of funds
trust.
OPTIONS SAFETY-NET RULES OUT PEP STATUS
There were at least two unusual ideas. John Govett, which has a range of
index funds, some using derivatives, launched the UK Safeguard Fund which
aims to replicate the performance of the FT-SE 100.
The use of options is meant as a safeguard against sharp falls, but it also
means that the trust does not qualify for Pep status.
Hargreaves Lansdowne, the Bristol-based independent financial adviser,
launched the Warrant Portfolio Trust, its first unit trust, which invests in
all types of these geared (and therefore risky) investments.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6726 Investment Offices, NEC.
    P6733 Trusts, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
