<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal Pensions
(28): Going at 50? It's trickier than you think - Taxation / The bulk of the
fund must be used immediately to buy an annuity, so the timing of the
purchase is critical. However, Inland Revenue rules do not normally permit
any delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When personal pensions were launched in July 1988, the government and life
offices spent millions advertising the flexibility of this modern product.
But in practice the Revenue's rigid tax rules and the pension providers'
restrictive contract terms create an investment environment where genuine
flexibility is sadly lacking.
There are three main trouble spots to watch out for.
Retirement annuity pensions
Until personal pensions replaced them in July 1988, retirement annuity
pensions (RAPs) were the main product for the self-employed and for
employees who did not have access to an occupational scheme. New RAPs were
not available after this date, but policyholders could continue to pay
contributions to existing contracts.
If you have an RAP but want to extend your investment choice, it is possible
to take out one or more personal pension plans, but the two types of pension
operate under very different tax rules and higher earners risk losing
valuable tax reliefs if they mix contributions.
Martin Korn, partner, financial services, with chartered accountants Blick
Rothenburg, said: 'Once you pay in to both policies, then the personal
pension contribution limits automatically apply to all contributions for
that tax year.
As the table shows, the RAP maximum contribution limits are generally lower
as a percentage of 'net relevant earnings' - the earnings on which your
pension premiums are based. But unlike personal pensions, RAPs are not
affected by the 'earnings cap' which restricts the earnings on which
contributions can be based to Pounds 76,800 for the current tax year.
According to actuaries Bacon &amp; Woodrow, employees earning over the 'net
relevant earnings threshold' for 1994-95 who want to pay maximum
contributions should stick to the RAP or use the 'alternate year funding'
method whereby contributions are paid to the RAP in one tax year and to the
personal pension in the next. Any RAP tax relief lost during the personal
pension contribution year can be mopped up through the Revenue's 'carry
forward' rules, but you will need expert advice for this complex exercise.
There are other important differences between the two individual pension
plans. Korn said: 'Despite their attractions for higher earners, RAPs cannot
be used to opt out of the state earnings-related pension scheme (Serps) or
to take employer contributions. For both of these features you need a
personal pension.'
Company schemes
The driving force behind the personal pension bandwagon is the apparent
portability that they offer to young people who expect to change jobs and
want to take their pension plan with them.
In practice, however, problems arise when the new company offers membership
of an occupational pension scheme. In most cases it is best to join company
schemes in order to benefit from employer contributions, a guaranteed
pension linked to salary and generous family protection insurances. However,
under Revenue regulations, with a few minor exceptions, it is not possible
to belong to an occupational pension scheme and to continue payments into a
personal pension, due to the different tax rules.
Unfortunately, investors who stop payments in the early years to a typical
regular-premium personal pension plan, in order to join the company scheme,
will find that most of their personal pension contributions have been
absorbed by the provider's administration charges and the adviser's
commission.
To avoid this problem, use a fee-based adviser for the personal pension, so
that the plan is set up on a nil-commission basis; or pay a series of single
premiums, which avoids the high up-front commissions associated with
regular-premium plans. Both methods allow you to reduce, stop and restart
contributions without penalty.
If you are locked in to a commission-based regular-premium plan, most
providers are prepared to redirect the contributions into a free-standing
additional voluntary contribution (FSAVC) plan. The FSAVC is used to top up
company pensions, and is governed by occupational scheme tax rules.
However, this option assumes that you can afford to pay contributions to the
life office as well as the company scheme. Moreover, while topping up
company pensions is a good idea, your first choice should always be the
employer's group AVC scheme, which is likely to offer better value for money
than the FSAVC due to economies of scale.
And at retirement . . .
Under personal pension rules, it is possible to retire at any age between 50
and 75. This may sound flexible, but in practice the rules are extremely
restrictive. Once the retirement date is reached, under most providers'
contracts, the bulk of the fund must be used immediately to buy an annuity
which provides the regular income for life. (The recent White Paper
suggested that this restriction will go in 1997, but details of the change
are not yet available.) Normally you cannot change your mind once you have
handed over your lump sum, and if you die the fund falls back into the life
office's coffers.
The level of income secured will depend partly upon the size of the fund and
partly on the prevailing annuity rates, which are broadly based on
long-dated gilt yields. Since these yields fluctuate significantly, the
timing of the annuity purchase is critical, yet the Revenue does not
normally permit any delay.
For wealthier individuals who are prepared to take a gamble, there are
options that allow the fund to continue to benefit from investment growth,
but if the fund value falls, so does your income.
A handful of providers sell annuities that leave the fund invested on a
unit-linked or with-profits basis; while a second option - phased retirement
 -allows you to divide your pension fund and buy, for example, three
separate annuities at age 65, 70 and 75, instead of using the entire fund to
purchase a single annuity. The delay in the final annuity purchase, which
has to be made by age 75, should secure a better income, because rates are
based on life expectancy, among other factors.
Staggered vesting replaces the one-off annuity purchase with a series of
annual transactions. This complex process can be very expensive, and you
lose access to the tax-free cash which is used to provide part of the annual
income.
If you are interested in these alternatives, expert advice is essential,
because you forfeit the guaranteed annuity income in return for the
potential of a higher income if investment conditions are favourable and
annuity rates improve.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
    Maximum contributions to personal pension plans and retirement
                    annuity pensions for 1994-95
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
                      % of net
                      relevant
                      earnings           NRE
                         (NRE)     threshold
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Age           PPP*        RAP       (Pounds)
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Up to 35     17.5        17.5         76,800
36-45        20.0        17.5         87,771
46-50        25.0        17.5        109,714
51-55        30.0        20.0        115,200
56-60        35.0        22.5        119,466
61-75        40.0        27.5        111,709
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
* Earnings on which PPP contributions are based are capped at
Pounds76,800 for the 1994-95 tax year.
What the table shows:
1, If your earnings fall on the threshold, you can contribute the same
amount to either plan or to a combination of both.
2, If you are over age 35 and your earnings fall below the threshold,
you can make higher contributions to PPPs.
3, If your earnings fall above the threshold, you can make higher
contributions to RAPs.
