<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal Pensions
(26): Glad tidings from an ill wind - Alternatives to the life companies /
Non-life providers will hope to exploit the poor image of inflexible
products and mis-selling that has damaged the insurance companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies from outside the life assurance industry are now gearing
themselves up to make their second attempt at grabbing an important share of
the personal pensions business. In the past, however, they have failed to
overcome the barrier of investor indifference.
New hope for the non-lifers springs essentially from the so-called 'hard'
disclosure of commissions and charges on life policies, which comes into
effect next January. These non-life providers will also be seeking to
exploit the poor image of inflexible products and mis-selling which has so
badly damaged the life companies in recent months.
When personal pensions legislation was introduced in the mid-1980s, the
government went out of its way to ensure that the new pensions products
would no longer be confined to the life assurance closed shop.
It was expected that unit trust companies, building societies and banks
would all participate in the exciting new markets, providing an important
new layer of competition for the life companies.
But it didn't work out like that. Although new entrants appeared, most
providers of unit trust pensions, such as Fidelity or Midland Bank,
eventually either pulled out or switched to life assurance vehicles. Only a
handful, such as Gartmore, Invesco and NM Rothschild, are still in business
with niche products.
They found marketing difficult when they could not use the life assurance
distribution channels. Lower charges made the non-life pensions products
inherently attractive, but the market turned out not to be very
price-sensitive - a consequence of the life industry's ability to conceal
its costs.
Administration also turned out to be something of a nightmare for providers
such as unit trust companies, which are used to handling simple transactions
involving straightforward products.
While the life offices sold millions of personal pension plans, the non-life
companies could only gain a toehold in the market, albeit probably towards
the higher-value end of the spectrum. Fidelity had around 3,000 clients, for
instance, when it pulled the plug in 1993.
It is possible, however, that the sales techniques which proved so
successful for the life companies will now rebound against them.
One non-life provider which has remained in business, however, is the
intermediary and consultancy group Pointon York, which is using the
framework for self-invested personal pensions (Sipps) which were introduced
in the 1989 Budget. Sipps can be invested in a range of assets in a tailored
and transparent way.
Mr Nigel Goodhew, a Pointon York director, says that a Sipp is the right
product for between 5 and 10 per cent of UK earners, but that 'my problem is
how to get to them'. So far the whole Sipp market embraces only about 3,000
clients.
However, Mr Goodhew expects Sipps to get a shot in the arm from hard
commission disclosure and greater job mobility for executives. He thinks
there will be 50,000 Sipps in existence by the year 2000.
An unexpected new entrant to the personal pensions market last February was
Foreign &amp; Colonial Investment Trust, which has extended its long-established
regular savings scheme (which is a particularly economical way of buying
shares in the investment trust) so that it can handle personal pension
plans.
Key features of the F &amp; C plan include low costs and flexibility, so that
there are none of the penalties that life companies can impose for reduced
contributions or missed instalments. However, savers are also likely to need
advice on how to handle the risks of a single stock market-based investment
in the years immediately preceding retirement.
In general, it is the absence of a developed infrastructure of fee-charging
advisers that has inhibited the growth of non-life personal pensions in the
UK. The question is whether the new disclosure climate will push the market
firmly enough in the non-life direction.
Fidelity is trying to tackle the market in a different way. It is drawing on
the experience of its American parent, which has successfully exploited the
trend towards company 'money purchase' pension schemes in the US.
So Fidelity has launched a unit trust-based company scheme, reckoning that
it is more practical to reach investors through their employing company than
directly through individual personal pension plans. The rather pessimistic
implication, however, is that Fidelity thinks it is always likely to be very
expensive to sell plans directly.
But a few more new entrants on the lines of F &amp; C might help popularise the
idea that life and pensions do not automatically go together.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
