<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal Pensions
(25): Family affairs - The choice for small businesses / Flexibility, cost
and the nature of your firm will be the deciding factors, but advice is
needed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Small businesses have several pension options, and the final choice will
depend on the required level of investment control, flexibility and cost.
Independent advice on a fee basis is essential for this market.
Small self-administered schemes
The most popular pension arrangement for family businesses is the small
self-administered scheme (SSAS). These are classed as occupational pension
schemes, and are extremely tax-efficient but can be expensive to run.
Membership, which is restricted to a maximum of 12, tends to be limited to
directors of the company. The trustees are chosen by the directors, but the
scheme also has to appoint a 'pensioner' trustee, approved by the Inland
Revenue, to provide advice on technical aspects and to ensure that, if the
scheme is wound up, the process meets with the Revenue's approval.
SSASs offer members a maximum pension of two-thirds of final salary
(restricted for some higher earners), which is secured through the purchase
of an annuity at retirement. The purchase can be made at any time up to age
75. There is also a substantial tax-free cash lump sum at retirement,
death-in-service and death-in-retirement benefits. Spouse and dependants'
benefits are automatically included.
Permitted investments include quoted stocks and shares, pooled investments
such as unit and investment trusts, cash funds, and commercial property.
Property is of particular interest to small companies, many of which use
their SSAS fund to purchase new business premises. However, this must be
done on an arms-length basis and a commercial rent must be charged.
The fund can be used to provide a loan to the company, again on arms-length
terms, and to purchase shares in the company. SSAS funds normally are exempt
from Department of Social Security rules that restrict self-investment to 5
per cent.
Although employees can pay up to 15 per cent of salary into the scheme, most
SSASs are funded purely by company contributions, since this reduces the
overall National Insurance bill. These contributions are tax-deductible and,
since they are based on the projected final salary at retirement, they are
virtually unlimited, although restrictions may apply in future.
Under Revenue rules, you can run only one SSAS at a time, which makes the
choice of provider extremely important. There are two main options: fully
self-administered, and 'hybrid' schemes. The former allow the administration
and investment to be run separately, whereas the two functions are combined
under a hybrid. Hybrid providers - the life offices - require a minimum
investment of about Pounds 5,000 a year in their own funds, although
contributions in excess of this can be invested by the client or his
stockbroker.
As a rule of thumb, the hybrid SSAS, which charges on a percentage basis, is
thought to be more cost-effective for annual premiums of less than Pounds
10,000 to Pounds 12,000. Where contributions exceed this amount, the
flat-rate fees charged on the fully self-administered SSAS start to look
attractive.
Advisers may also recommend executive pension plans (EPPs). These are
similar to SSASs, but the entire fund is run by the life office, and on
retirement the annuity has to be purchased immediately. Also, from September
this year, the Inland Revenue will impose restrictions on the maximum
contributions that can be paid into an EPP.
Personal pension options
If you are interested in a simpler and cheaper alternative to the SSAS, it
is worth considering a group personal pension (GPP) or self-invested
personal pensions (SIPPs).
GPPs are a collection of individual personal pensions. Maximum annual
employee and employer contributions are limited to 17.5 per cent of earnings
(more for employees over 35) and the proceeds are used to buy an annuity at
retirement, which can be at any time between age 50 and 75.
Normally, under the providers' contract conditions, the annuity has to be
purchased immediately the selected retirement age is reached, although the
recent White Paper on pension reform indicated that there would be greater
flexibility for annuities from April 1997. Most providers combine the
administration and investment functions, and insist that contributions are
invested in their own funds.
Self-invested personal pensions allow you to manage your own investments.
They can be used by individuals, groups of employees and Schedule-D
taxpayers such as partnerships.
The main attraction of the SIPP is its ability to unbundle the investment
and administration, to provide a clearer charging structure and greater
investment flexibility. With an SIPP, you can either run the investment
portfolio yourself or appoint your own stockbroker. This makes it possible
to change the investment manager while leaving the underlying administration
and legal structure in place - an option not possible under most
conventional personal pensions.
SIPPs follow the basic contribution and benefit rules for personal pensions
and, as with all plans, there is a monetary cap on the total earnings to
which contributions relate. This is Pounds 76,800 for the 1994-95 tax year.
SIPP funds can invest in UK and overseas stocks and shares, unit trusts and
investment trusts, insurance company managed funds and unit-linked funds,
deposit accounts and commercial property. The last includes new offices for
the business, provided the property is leased back on a commercial basis. It
is possible for the SIPP to borrow on the strength of the pension fund to
help with property purchase.
SIPPs are normally run on an individual basis, but if the funds are grouped
together it can result in greater investment scope and economies of scale.
Inevitably the SIPP v SSAS argument comes down to a matter of horses for
courses. Andrew Hague, manager of the SSAS department at consulting
actuaries Barnett Waddingham, said: 'At present, we believe SSASs offer
greater flexibility, particularly on the investment scope, the higher
contribution rates and the timing of the annuity purchase.'
But John Moret, pensions manager at Provident Life, said that SIPPs had
other attractions: 'SIPPs offer greater simplicity, lower costs and,
probably most important of all, individual hands-on control of the fund. In
addition, while there are contribution limits on SIPPs, there are no limits
on benefits, as is the case with SSASs.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
