<PROFILE>_AN-EGODBAHJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940715
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal Pensions
(24): How not to fall into a trough? - The risk / Retire when the stock
market or annuity rates are low, and your pension will suffer. The industry
is seeking a solution to the problem
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consider the position of someone who retired on a personal pension the day
after the stock market crash of October 1987. Or, to take a more immediate
example of how personal pension holders are hostage to market forces: the
individual who retired earlier this year, when annuity rates, reflecting the
very low yields available on 15-year gilts, fell to their lowest level in
decades.
For two people whose retirements were separated by Black Monday of October
1987, said Mr Ron Spill, director of pensions at Legal and General, 'the
difference in the value of their pensions is 20 per cent.'
In an employer-sponsored defined benefit scheme, it is the employer who
bears the investment risk; and because benefits are paid out from a pool
over a very long period, fluctuations in market values are not usually
significant.
But the challenge that personal pension providers now have before them is to
devise investment strategies which help to minimise the volatility of
investment returns, while maximising returns from the highest yielding
securities. The same question of investment volatility applies to
increasingly popular money-purchase, defined-contribution schemes.
Moreover, the Labour party has indicated that it would like personal pension
providers to build into contracts a minimum guaranteed level of benefit into
contracts - a measure which would make a solution to the investment issue
imperative.
Mr Nigel Chambers, director at actuarial consultants Johnston Douglas,
argues that the answer for the individual who wants to protect himself
against a stock market crash just before retirement date is to 'make sure
you are not invested in equities'.
Indeed, most of the structures intended to reduce the investment risks of
personal pensions involve the gradual shift of the portfolio into
fixed-interest securities as the individual approaches retirement date.
Gartmore, the UK fund management company, has a product which invests 90 per
cent of an individual's pension fund in equities up until the 40th birthday.
Then, over the next 25 years, investments are gradually moved out of
equities and into fixed-interest investments - a process which accelerates
between the 60th and 65th birthdays. Thus, if yields on bonds have fallen
sharply, at least the individual will have the benefit of the sharp
investment gains on bond prices which should have accrued in the preceding
months.
An alternative solution was launched last year by Mercury Asset Management's
life insurance arm, Mercury Life. While it is initially available only to
prospective clients with Pounds 500,000 or more to invest - making it
suitable only for large group personal pensions or money-purchase accounts -
the technique shows promise for personal pension holders as well.
Using a complex formula that involves the use of equity derivatives, the
'guarantee fund' invests 99 per cent of all contributions in an investment
pool, while the remaining 1 per cent goes into a reserve fund. The reserve
fund uses derivatives to ensure that the individual will earn at least 90
per cent of the average daily market value of the units in the investment
pool, and retain those profits even if the stock markets fall sharply in
ensuing years.
Alternatively, some argue, the liability stream of a personal pension
requires the UK government to be much more imaginative and flexible in its
design of investment securities used to fund the budget deficit.
Mr Stewart Ritchie, pensions director at Scottish Equitable, says: 'The
basic problem is the structure of the cash flow.' What is needed, he
suggests, is a very long-dated UK government gilt which pays no interest in
its early years - while the pension plan holder is still employed and saving
for retirement - but pays index-linked benefits in later years. Such a
security could be purchased with a lump sum on, say, an individual's 40th
birthday and accrue interest at, say, some margin above retail prices until
the 65th birthday is reached. The index-linked payments would operate
thereafter.
Mr Ritchie argues that the new instrument would ensure that final returns to
personal pension holders at least bear some relationship to the income
earned during a lifetime at work. Presumably, salary will have increased
broadly in line with inflation during the individual's working life,
matching the accrued interest he will earn on retirement.
Mr Ritchie is not alone in calling for new instruments to meet the
investment objectives of personal and money-purchase pensions. The
left-of-centre think-tank, the Institute for Public Policy Studies, has also
called for the creation of a new instrument that would have a capital value
linked to an index of national average earnings.
So a broad spectrum of the pensions industry has at least recognised the
need to rethink the appropriate investment strategy. It remains to be seen
which solution will prove the most effective for policyholders.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT943-14124</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EGODBAHIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940715
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal Pensions
(23): With care, you can pass some of it on - The beneficiaries / Most
personal pensions are set up under the provider's universal trust scheme. A
form with the application invites you to say whom you would like the death
benefits to go to
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you do not have access to a company pension scheme, the investments
accumulated under a personal pension or its predecessor, a retirement
annuity pension, are likely to represent your most important asset.
While the primary purpose of any pension plan is to provide the maximum
income in retirement, most people would also like to pass on as much of the
pension fund as possible to the next generation.
There are two distinct stages to consider here, namely: the contribution
period during your working life, when you are building up your fund; and the
benefit period in retirement, when you are drawing the pension income.
The contribution period
Personal pensions usually have a clearly identifiable value at any given
time up to retirement, and most providers guarantee to return the full fund
value on death before retirement. This is paid tax-free to the nominated
beneficiary.
Under a unit linked or unitised with-profits policy, where the contributions
buy units in a pooled fund, the value of your fund is simply the value of
your units. However, 'traditional' with-profits funds, still used by a few
personal pension providers and the most common choice for retirement annuity
pensions, were not unitised. Here the value of your fund on death before
retirement may be calculated in one of several ways.
Some providers return the value of contributions with interest paid at
various rates from 3 per cent to 9 per cent. Others return the value of
contributions without interest or make no return at all. However, if you
have one of these policies, do not automatically assume you have been
cheated. Low-return or no-return policies usually offer a higher return in
order to provide better pension benefits, while separate life assurance is
often sold to provide the death benefits.
Tony Tollerton, senior technical manager at Sun Life, warned: 'It is
important to maintain that life cover, even if you stop paying in to the
policy; otherwise, if you die, your dependants may receive little back from
the pension provider.' Tollerton advised individuals with older policies to
check the death benefits, and if necessary take out further life assurance
to top up the tax-free lump sum for dependants.
It is also important to check that your policies are written under trust.
Pension plans established in this way avoid potential inheritance tax (IHT)
liabilities, because any death benefits can be paid direct to the nominated
beneficiary rather than pass through the deceased's estate. Even where you
intend to pass on everything to your spouse, which normally would not
involve IHT, if you both die at the same time or within a short period of
each other, then your children may have to pay IHT on the benefits from the
pension plan.
Most personal pensions automatically are set up under the provider's
universal trust scheme, and an expression-of-wish form is included with the
application, which invites you to set out who you would like the death
benefits to go to. Under these trust schemes, the life office acts as
trustee and has discretionary power to make the payments to the appropriate
person in the same way as occupational pension scheme trustees operate.
Your beneficiary does not have to be a spouse or a dependent child, and if
you are unmarried you can nominate your mother or your common-law partner,
for example. However, Ian McKenna, partner with independent financial
adviser Blyth McKenna, stressed: 'It is vital to review the beneficiary form
at regular intervals. We have had cases where the original nomination was
not changed when a client got married and had children, so that when he died
the nominated beneficiary was still the client's mother or former
girlfriend.'
Normally in these cases the trustees would try to sort out the most suitable
beneficiary, but this could be a long, complex and potentially acrimonious
process, particularly where the individual had been married several times or
had children by more than one partner.
While universal trust schemes are common practice today, this was not the
case with retirement annuity pensions. If you have one of these older
policies, check whether you have nominated a beneficiary and, if not, ask
your adviser or provider to sort out a trust arrangement for you.
The retirement period
When you reach retirement, the bulk of your personal pension or retirement
annuity fund must be used to buy an annuity from a life office which
guarantees the regular pension income.
If you contracted out of the state earnings-related pension scheme (Serps),
the element of the fund which was built up from rebates of national
insurance contributions, known as 'appropriate rights', must be used to buy
an annuity that includes a spouse's pension if you die.
It is up to you what level of dependant's benefits you secure with the
annuity purchased by the rest of the fund, but any extra guarantees, such as
a spouse's pension, will reduce the annuity income by up to 16 per cent.
Apart from buying a spouse's pension, it is also possible to protect your
fund. Under a basic annuity, once you hand over your lump sum, it is gone
for good, even if you die shortly afterwards.
The alternative is to buy a guarantee that, if you die within the first five
years of retirement, the balance of your pension fund will be paid to your
beneficiary. A five-year guarantee is likely to reduce the annuity income by
about 1.6 per cent, while a 10-year guarantee, offered by some providers,
would reduce your pension by about 6 per cent.
There are other options at retirement for those who do not want to be locked
into a conventional annuity and wish to keep the fund fully invested.
</TEXT>
