<PROFILE>_AN-EGODBAG9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940715
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Equities (Regional
reports) (14): US analysts are cautious on third-quarter earnings growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Although the second quarter of 1994 had few of the nasty shocks that so
paralysed the US stock market in the first three months of the year, it
still proved a difficult period for traders and investors.
After staging a halting rally from April through to mid-May, share prices
turned tail in the closing weeks of the quarter. Between June 14 and June
30, the market lost all of the 6 per cent gain it had earned in the previous
nine weeks.
Those losses meant that the Dow Jones Industrial Average had fallen for two
consecutive quarters for the first time since 1984.
By the close of trading on the quarter's final day, the Dow stood at
3,624.96, down 11 points points, or 0.3 per cent since March 31. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was at 444.27, having fallen less than two points
during the quarter; while the Nasdaq composite index, under pressure from
heavily-sold technology stocks, finished at 705.96, down 38 points, or 5 per
cent.
As in the first three months of the year, trading during the quarter was
dominated by rising interest rates. From the start, the market struggled to
make much headway amid concern that the Federal Reserve would tighten
monetary policy further in an attempt to cool down the overheating economy
and stifle inflation. When the Fed did raise rates, pushing the federal
funds rate from 3.5 per cent to 3.75 per cent on April 18, share prices
dropped sharply.
Yet, within a week, the market psychology began to change. From fearing
another rate increase, Wall Street started to look forward to one, with
analysts judging that one more tightening of monetary policy would be enough
to appease the inflation-sensitive bond market without inflicting serious
damage on equity market sentiment.
Consequently, when the Fed raised rates again in mid-May, the stock market
rallied. At the time, investors assumed that the Fed had finished raising
interest rates, at least for the rest of the summer. Thus, over the next
month the Dow advanced 140 points, or 4 per cent, to peak at 3,814.83 on
June 14.
The gains were fuelled by the belief that long-term interest rates had
stabilised - the yield on the long bond was hovering around 7.35 per cent
for most of that time - and that the settled outlook for monetary policy,
combined with still-growing corporate earnings, would revive investor demand
for stocks.
Those quietly optimistic expectations, however, were overshadowed in the
final weeks by several external factors which conspired to drag prices lower
across the board. They were: rising commodity prices, which revived the bond
market's inflation jitters, the political crisis in the Korean peninsula,
and a weak dollar. The last of these inflicted the most damage, as the US
currency's plunge below Y100 against the yen sent stock and bond prices
tumbling, amid predictions that the Fed would have to raise interest rates
to protect the ailing dollar.
By the end of June, the growing feeling that the markets had overreacted to
the dollar's decline, and that another rate increase was not on the cards,
suggested the third quarter might get off to a positive start. Yet analysts
cautioned that the expected downturn in the economy during the second half
of the year would probably slow the rate of corporate earnings growth over
the summer.
In Mexico, the stock market plunged 19 per cent in the opening two weeks of
the quarter after US interest rates were raised, but then rallied strongly
in late April after US, Canada and Mexico signed an arrangement for fighting
exchange rate turbulence among their currencies. For the remainder of the
quarter, fears of higher US interest rates and continuing political problems
with the rebels in Chiapas held prices back, and the IPC index ended the
quarter at 2,262.6, down 150 points, or 6 per cent.
As on Wall Street, Canadian stocks were troubled throughout the second
quarter by rising domestic interest rates. Over the three months, the
Toronto Stock Exchange composite index fell more than 300 points, or 7 per
cent, to end at 4,025.25.
</TEXT>
