<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Equities (11):
Accentuating the positive - Tokyo has risen while other markets have fallen,
and foreign investors have done particularly well. Is this the moment to put
money into one of the new Japanese funds?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan, in the second quarter of the year, was one of the few markets to buck
the global decline. Fund managers overweight in Tokyo this year should have
a nice story for their trustees, or at least some significant paper gains to
set against losses on Wall Street, London and the main European markets.
Sterling- and dollar-based investors in Japan were helped by the strong yen
and continued buying by foreign investors.
The Nikkei 225 index marked a two-year high in mid-June, and showed a total
return in the quarter, as measured by the FT-Actuaries World indices, of
almost 8 per cent in sterling terms, and some 50 per cent more for
dollar-based investors.
Given Japan's high weighting in the world equity index, reading Tokyo
correctly has been a key factor for investment returns.
But who got the weightings right? Most fund managers keep their investment
decisions close to their chests, but if market gossip is anything to go by,
end-June valuations should be good for Nikko Securities, the Dutch Robeco
funds and Germany's Commerz International Capital Management. Commerz is
believed to have doubled its Japanese exposure at the end of March.
Against the negative total return globally for sterling investors in the
quarter (minus 0.5 per cent ), assuming weighted averages across the FT
world index, what should be the next move?
The terrible twins of fear and greed continue to drive most markets, and
fear is now in the ascendancy, not least because of chaos and confusion in
global bond markets and the associated concern over higher interest rates,
especially in the United States.
Brave new investors in Japan need to leave fear behind, and concentrate
instead on hope. The Nikkei has done well this year, especially for
non-Japanese investors, and a number of new Japanese unit (and mutual) funds
are about to be unleashed in both London and New York.
But is Japan right for tapping? Even greater political uncertainty comes
with the arrival of an untried socialist prime minister heading a coalition
government which has, in effect, given many of the levers of power back to
the long-ruling right-wing Liberal Democrats. The crucial trade talks with
Washington are getting nowhere fast, and the yen is ever-rising. On the
surface, this is not a good investment scenario.
But there are targets to aim at. The higher yen hits exports, but almost
certainly it will be an excuse for Japanese companies to become even more
efficient, to trim paternalistic work practices and to shed surplus labour.
The OECD's latest projection of economic growth sees real GDP output in
Japan rising sharply in 1995.
Another target is the Nikkei index itself. It has been fair weather so far
this year, but the end-June close of 20,600 is still little more than half
its high of 1989. Some optimistic Tokyo market-watchers think that, over
time, markets, like water, reach their own level; and that, in the long
haul, why should Japan, coming out of recession and with some encouraging
corporate profit forecasts, buck this trend? For non-Japanese holders, the
currency factor is also an important consideration.
A significant factor could be the non-Japanese investment overhang. A number
of American and (even more) European funds got into Tokyo at the top of the
market, and many are waiting to cash in at original investment levels, given
that the earnings yield is negligible. But other funds switched to Japan
earlier this year, and are in for the long haul and for the market (and
economic) recovery. As long as the Japanese currency remains strong, they
are likely to maintain global weightings in Tokyo.
Japan is certainly not without risk, but a strong combination of domestic
deregulation and a heavy Yen could transform the Japanese economy. The
Nikkei seems to have a floor at around the 20,000 level, but the upside
could be significant in the medium term.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
