<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (6): Waiting for the
dollar - Overseas investment 4 / The US / If the currency were to
strengthen, it would magnify any growth in the stock market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you want to invest in the United States, there are a number of different
ways of going about it. But at the moment, many investors may see it as a
very big 'if'.
Nigel Sidebottom, a portfolio manager at stockbrokers Gerrard Vivian Gray,
says he and his colleagues took the decision more than a year ago to
withdraw their most aggressive portfolios from the US altogether. More
conservative portfolios still have a small amount of US exposure, but
Sidebottom says he can see little reason to increase that in the foreseeable
future.
The US is further ahead in the economic cycle than the rest of the developed
world. Rapid growth has slowed down, and the Federal Reserve Bank has
already raised interest rates by 1.25 percentage points. Bond and stock
markets have been jittery, with equities following the bond market's every
move, and reacting badly to negative economic news, but showing little
response to more positive data.
US investors have been sending huge amounts of money abroad - American fund
managers were largely responsible for the soaring stock markets in east Asia
at the end of last year. Since those markets started to drop, however, much
of the money has been withdrawn. Some of those funds may be finding their
way back into US stock markets.
But if interest rates continue to rise, the same investors who stampeded
into domestic and overseas equities during the past year or two, driven out
of deposit-based investments by the meagre rates, may start a stampede in
the opposite direction - which would not bode well for share prices.
One brighter point for overseas investors is the possibility of the dollar
strengthening after a prolonged period of weakness. This would magnify any
stock market growth, and could even make a stagnant market profitable. On
the expectation of that, some fund managers are keeping money in the US, or
even increasing their weightings. However, the dollar has not shown much
sign of strength yet.
UK investors who look at the evidence and decide that the US is a good home
for at least part of their portfolio at the moment have an enormous choice
of collective investment vehicles. There are more than 100 unit trusts in
the North America sector, offering a wide range of specialisms, including
currency bear and bull funds, index-trackers, reverse index funds, special
situations, recovery funds and biotechnology, as well as general trusts.
North American investment trusts are thinner on the ground: there are only
seven in total, four of which are specialist smaller companies funds. There
are also a few predominantly or entirely US-invested funds in other sectors,
such as Lazard's North American Gas trust and the River &amp; Mercantile
American split-capital trust.
For the average investor who does not have a strong view on US market
prospects, a sensible approach could be to pick a general international fund
with some US exposure (most have between 5 and 25 per cent in the US), and
leave the precise asset allocation up to the professionals.
</TEXT>
