<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (2): Buy a stake in
other people's economies - It's not just a way of spreading risk, says
Gillian O'Connor, in this introduction to a sequence of articles on
investing overseas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some of the canniest investors seldom invest overseas. They like to be able
to keep an eye on the businesses they are backing. That's fine for a
stockpicker as talented as American sage Warren Buffett. But most
professional investors believe in getting a spread of investments in their
portfolios: that means both different types of business and businesses in
different countries.
Putting some money overseas is a well established tradition in Britain. Our
oldest investment trust is called Foreign and Colonial. Foreign investment
is not just a form of risk-spreading: it is also a way of getting a stake in
economies which appear to have better prospects for growth than Britain. And
it allows investors to participate in industries which do not exist in
Britain.
For example, the Japanese economy and stock market is out of synch with
those of other main world economies: the decline came later than it did in
the US and Europe, and enthusiasts for Japanese shares argue that they now
offer the same kind of potential as UK shares did early in 1993.
Or, suppose there is a world commodity boom. Since Britain does not produce
commodities, the immediate effect would be a rise in the cost of imports,
and ultimately inflation. But if British investors have shares in the
overseas companies which do produce commodities, they will participate in
their prosperity.
UK pension funds and insurance companies had a substantial proportion of
their assets overseas, even when exchange controls made foreign investment
an expensive hobby. Since the abolition of exchange controls in 1979, their
overseas interests have increased.
American investors have been slower to move abroad - understandably, given
the importance of their own economy. But US pension funds have belatedly
admitted that it makes sense for them to put at least some of thir eggs in a
foreign basket. And in 1993 American private investors joined the rush to
invest abroad, mainly through mutual funds. One large US broker has
recommended all its private clients to have a fifth of their investment
portfolios overseas by the end of this century.
The growing American interest in foreign stock markets has two consequences
for British investors. The sheer scale of American buying power means that
US investment fancies tend to be self-fulfilling, particularly in smaller
stock markets. But if that buying slows or reverses, the departure of the
investment 'tourists' can have a devastating effect on the markets they have
patronised. US pension-fund money is generally expected to be in for the
long haul, while mutual-fund investors may prove more fickle.
Most British firms which manage money for private clients have long
recommended some overseas exposure, and tend to allocate specific chunks of
client portfolios to overseas markets. Fund managers will suggest different
portfolio splits for different clients. Very broadly, the greater your
desire for income from your investments, and the more worried you are about
risk, the smaller the overseas chunk. Normally that means that, the less
affluent you are or the nearer you are to retirement, the more parochial you
need to be.
The table of benchmarks shows how one fund manager splits funds for
different types of client in a 'neutral' world: ie, one in which he does not
expect big changes in currency or stock markets. In practice, the actual
allocations will usually differ substantially from the benchmarks for
strategic reasons.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Possible portfolio benchmarks (%)
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Asset type            Growth  Balanced    Income
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Index linked gilts        20        15         -
Conventional gilts         -        10        30
UK Equities               40        45        50
Overseas Equities         40        30        20
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Kleinwort Benson Private Client Management
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
