<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / World Commodities Prices: Copper's break out pulls other
base metals higher - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER prices broke up out of their recent ranges at the London Metal
Exchange yesterday afternoon, pulling other metals higher.
Fresh speculative interest fuelled a rise that triggered stop-loss buying
orders above Dollars 2,475 a tonne for three months delivery. The price
closed at Dollars 2,482.50, up Dollars 35, before being trimmed back to
Dollars 2,478 in after hours trading. Some traders expectations of a further
decline in LME warehouse stocks were supportive.
ALUMINIUM tracked copper but was not able fully to match its gains as there
is a sizeable resistance area stretching up towards the Dollars 1,550 a
tonne level for the three months position, which closed at Dollars 1,52.50,
up Dollars 10.
Three months ZINC finally broke above Dollars 1,000 a tonne as the bullish
enthusiasm of copper and aluminium spilled over. Stop-loss buying took the
price up to the day's high, with final business at Dollars 1,006, a Dollars
12 gain.
LEAD was also steadier, although three months metal continued to meet
stubborn resistance near the Dollars 600-a-tonne level. It finished at
Dollars 596, up Dollars 4.
Compiled from Reuters
