<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / International Bonds: Canadian dollar sector revived by deals
aimed at retail buyers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After several days dominated by large offerings aimed at institutional
investors, the pattern shifted yesterday, as a spate of deals targeted at
the retail investor emerged in the Canadian dollar sector.
There has been a revival of interest in the sector, due largely to a heavy
schedule of nearly CDollars 2bn-worth of redemptions of outstanding bonds -
including a CDollars 650m Alberta deal - next month.
Many Benelux-based investors are looking for Canadian dollar bonds in which
to reinvest following the redemptions, particularly since Canadian dollar
yields are now higher than those for Belgian and Luxembourg franc bonds.
Until yesterday's rush of CDollars 375m-worth of new issues, there had been
little activity for about a month, but the forthcoming redemptions coupled
with a strengthening of the Canadian dollar encouraged borrowers to return
to the market, dealers said.
Canada's Federal Business Development Bank and Germany's L-Bank both
launched three-year deals, arranged by Barclays de Zoete Wedd and Goldman
Sachs respectively, while Norddeutsche Landesbank launched a five-year
offering via Hambros Bank.
At the longer end, Societe Quebecoise D'Assainissement des Eaux, a
provincial crown corporation, launched a 10-year deal, which would usually
be rather long-dated for retail investors. However, the 10 per cent coupon
is attractive to these buyers, who have been looking for this type of coupon
for some time.
Dealers said that institutional investors are not looking at the market, and
anyway would typically prefer larger, more liquid offerings.
In the sterling floating-rate note market, a unit of SG Warburg added Pounds
75m to an outstanding Pounds 150m issue. the offering pays a discounted
margin of 28 basis points over Libor.
Pohang Iron &amp; Steel filed with the US Securities and Exchange Commission a
shelf offering of up to Dollars 700m in debt securities and common stock,
Reuter reports.
The Korean steel producer said the proceeds from the sale would be used for
general corporate purposes including capital expenditures, debt refinancing
and overseas investments.
</TEXT>
