<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / International Company News: CBS forms joint ventures with
Westinghouse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CBS, the US television network, signed up three additional stations owned by
Westinghouse Electric as affiliates, in the process repairing some of the
damage done by the defection of eight other affiliates to Mr Rupert
Murdoch's Fox network in May.
Westinghouse and CBS also announced they would seek to extend their
ownership of broadcast television stations through a new joint company, to
be majority owned and managed by Group W, Westinghouse's broadcasting
company.
In addition, the two companies announced joint ventures in programming and
advertising sales.
For CBS, the deal brings VHF stations in three important US markets:
Philadelphia, the fourth-ranked market in the country, Boston (6th) and
Baltimore (22nd). CBS already owns a Philadelphia station, which will be
sold. Two of the stations are switching from NBC, with the third from ABC.
The deal has been under discussion for two months, the two companies said.
In recent days, CBS has dropped a proposed merger with home shopping group
QVC, which would have taken it into cable television, raising questions
about the future of its earlier strategy of relying on broadcast stations.
For Westinghouse, the joint ventures with CBS will provide extra resources
to expand Group W's operations. Mr Michael Jordan, the group's recently
appointed chief executive, has resisted selling the unit as part of an
overhaul of the troubled manufacturing group.
As part of yesterday's deal, Group W and CBS will form a joint programming
unit, to provide material to their own stations and others. The partnership
will not take effect until November 1995, when existing regulations end.
Group W will also own the majority stake in a new company formed by merging
the two group's advertising sales operations.
Mr Laurence Tisch, chairman and chief executive of CBS, said the deal
'further demonstrates our commitment to the network/affiliate system and our
firm belief in the future of broadcasting.'
</TEXT>
