FT  15 JUL 94 / International Company News: Malaysian mobile phone group
surges to MDollars 105m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Technology Resources Industries (TRI), the holding company for Cellular
Communications Network (Malaysia), Malaysia's largest mobile phone carrier,
has announced 95.6 per cent year-on-year growth in pre-tax profits, to
MDollars 105.97m (USDollars 40.9m), for the first half of 1994.
The results were well within market expectations of between MDollars 95m and
MDollars 120m.
Group turnover grew 49 per cent to MDollars 367.1m compared with a year ago,
and after-tax profits were up 120 per cent to MDollars 69.9m. The stock does
not pay a dividend.
The company recorded an extraordinary gain of MDollars 126.1m on the sale of
its non-telecommunications subsidiaries. Cellular Communications (Celcom)
contributed the bulk of profits, supplemented by smaller contributions from
the Malaysian Helicopter Services (MHS) subsidiary.
Analysts were pleased with the results, but expressed concern about the
company's disclosure policies. Earlier this year, UBS (East Asia), a member
of the Union Bank of Switzerland group of companies, had to postpone an
international offering of USDollars 400m in TRI euroconvertible bonds, after
European fund managers objected to discrepancies in profit forecasts.
