<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Hole left in local pockets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If there was one thing that Mr James Millar liked emphasising to visitors to
Wm Low's Dundee offices it was the contribution the headquarters made to the
local economy, writes James Buxton.
'We obtain almost all our professional services locally,' the chairman would
say. 'Even the taxi driver taking you to the station is benefiting. None of
that would happen if we were part of a group based in London.'
So it is poignant that the loss of Wm Low's independence will involve the
closure of its headquarters and probable redundancy for many of its 300
staff.
The takeover will mean the disappearance of a historic name from the
Scottish business scene. It also means a reduction in the modest number of
Scottish quoted companies.
Wm Low was founded in 1867 by two Dundee families. By 1914 the chain had
grown to 80 stores. Mr Millar, a terrier of a man, became managing director
in 1981, upgrading the supermarkets and expanding into northern England.
Mr Campbell Christie, general secretary of the Scottish Trade Union
Congress, said yesterday he was disappointed to see 'another Scottish
company bite the dust'. But it was better for Wm Low to be taken over than
to see it closing stores.
Dundee can absorb the loss of Wm Low's head office, despite unemployment of
11 per cent. But it badly needs some good news after last year's rancourous
industrial dispute and closure at the Timex electronics plant.
As for the customers, one said: 'The staff at Willie Low's are the nicest
and most polite of the supermarkets I go to.' Would she keep shopping there
when it became Tesco? 'Yes I would.'
</TEXT>
