<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Cuts Treasury driven, says Labour: Backbench Tories applaud
defence paper
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday accused the government of making cuts in the armed forces
to meet the Treasury's demand for financial stringency rather than for
operational reasons.
But backbench Conservative MPs, some of whom have expressed concern on this
issue in recent months, applauded the defence report, arguing that it would
enhance military effectiveness in the long term.
Mr Donald Anderson, a Labour defence spokesman, welcomed some of the
proposals in the document, including an enhanced role for the Territorial
Army and the creation of a rapid deployment force. But he questioned why, if
the cuts were justified, they were not part of the last defence review in
1990.
He claimed that the principle of cutting support services was undermined by
the fact that more than 70 per cent of Royal Air Force personnel sent to the
Gulf had been deemed support staff. 'Does that not show how spurious is this
distinction between support services and front line in a modern, integrated
service community?' he asked.
Tory MPs were satisfied with the statement by Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the
defence secretary, believing that the government was reducing waste rather
than operational effectiveness.
'They have sucked out a good deal of the fat and they have been very clever
by getting a lot of suggestions from people in the business,' said Sir Jerry
Wiggin, a Tory member of the Commons defence committee. 'They have broken
down the legacy of empire.'
Sir Archie Hamilton, a former defence minister, said: 'The concern all along
is whether we would lose any defence capability. Instead, we've had an
enhancement.'
A number of MPs were concerned that the Ministry of Defence would faces
further cuts in the forthcoming public expenditure survey. However, Mr
Rifkind has privately told MPs that he has an unwritten agreement with the
Treasury that defence will not be the target of further cuts.
A number of Tory and Labour MPs were concerned that their constituencies
would suffer job losses, and some Tories urged the government to reverse
specific proposals. Mr David Shaw was particularly concerned at the proposal
to transfer the Royal Military School for Music from Deal in his Dover
constituency. 'To remove the royal school . . . would tear the heart out of
the constituency,' he said.
</TEXT>
