<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Rosyth deprived of warships and jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Rosyth naval base in Fife is to lose its warships and be downgraded to a
naval support establishment, under the plans announced yesterday by Mr
Rifkind.
Although the base has escaped the closure which had earlier been feared,
there will still be considerable job losses and a serious impact on the
local economy.
Mr Rifkind said one of the two squadrons of minehunters now based there
would be moved to the Faslane submarine base on the Clyde while the other
would move to Portsmouth. The ships at Faslane would be nearer their
operational area, while the ships moving to Portsmouth mainly operated off
England and Wales.
Rosyth will retain the option of being an operating base if necessary and be
used for defence research, storage, accommodation and support for the
adjoining naval dockyard, which is unaffected.
The civilian workforce will fall from 1,300 to 600, and the number of
service personnel located there will be cut from 1,800 to 300. Mr Rifkind
said about 70 jobs would be created at Faslane.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said Scotland would 'bear its fair share,
but no more' of the job losses announced in the review. He said hundreds of
manufacturing jobs in Scotland would be secured by defence orders made
possible by the review.
Fife Regional Council dismissed the diminished role for Rosyth as
unacceptable. It said the base would be the target of resistance for trade
unions and local authorities, which are meeting to plan their campaign
today.
The council believes that last year the naval base was responsible for
securing 4,000 jobs outside the base in the local economy, to which it
contributed Pounds 180m. It believes that only 1,000 jobs will be sustained
by the scaled-down operation and its economic contribution will fall to
Pounds 75m.
Unemployment in the Dunfermline area would rise from 11 per cent to 15 per
cent after the cuts, the council said.
Mr Alex Salmond, leader of the Scottish National party, said last night:
'What kind of naval base will Rosyth be with no ships based there? A naval
base without ships has the same long-term prospects as a pub with no beer.'
