FT  15 JUL 94 / Broker fights Pounds 200,000 fine
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A stockbroker fined a record Pounds 200,000 by the Securities and Futures
Association for helping to sell the assets of a Kuwaiti client after Kuwaiti
assets were frozen after the 1990 Iraqi invasion yesterday won the right to
challenge the regulatory body's decision in the High Court.
Mr Anthony O'Sullivan, a former managing director of stockbrokers Sassoon
Europe, was given leave yesterday to appeal against the decision through a
judicial review. It is thought this is the first case of SFA disciplinary
proceedings being challenged in this way.
The client whose assets he helped sell is thought to be the Kuwaiti
Investment Office, the investment arm of the Kuwait government.
