<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / 'Tri-service' plan triumphs over tough vested interests:
Operational command unified
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The plan announced yesterday represents a hard-won victory by defence
ministry officials, over some stubborn vested interests, for the commonsense
idea of joint or 'tri-service' facilities.
The ministry has had to contend with the staunchly independent traditions of
the three services, as well as some more practical objections.
Under the new principle - referred by the ugly new word 'jointery' - there
is to be a tri-service hospital and a tri-service staff college. Joint
arrangements will be promoted in areas such as flying instruction, music
lessons and veterinary care.
Operational commands are by definition 'tri-service' as most wars are fought
on land, sea and air. A permanent tri-service operational headquarters will
be set up at Northwood, north-west of London.
Ministry officials believe a single establishment to oversee operations in
conflict zones will be better than what one called 'the current ad hoc
approach of setting up such a headquarters only in response to a developing
crisis'.
Senior officers are known to have doubts about concentrating operational
command in one, potentially vulnerable spot, however.
Plans to bring the services together in a 20,000-strong Rapid Deployment
Force, including men from the Parachute Regiment, Royal Marine commandos and
RAF aircraft, are expected to receive a warmer welcome.
The ministry has decided to make the naval hospital at Haslar, Hampshire a
joint institution and to close the hospitals at Aldershot, Hampshire, and
Wroughton, Wiltshire. All secondary medical care will be concentrated in a
tri-service agency.
A joint staff college is to be established by 1997, where officers will be
sent on 10-month courses in tactical and operational doctrine.
The ministry may use the Army school at Camberley, Surrey or the historic
naval college at Greenwich, south London.
