<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Unions launch campaign against 'a dirty trick'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trade unions representing defence workers plan a three-month campaign
against cuts in the worst affected areas of the country which have
Conservative MPs.
Mr Jack Dromey, national secretary of the TGWU general union, said last
night: 'Through a long, hot summer the unions will be asking why the party
of defence is betraying the defence workers.'
The IPMS civil service union, which represents 25,000 technical specialists
in the Ministry of Defence, said the 7,100 cut in civilian jobs announced
yesterday was on top 12,000 job losses announced under the Options for
Change programme.
Mr Paul Noon, the union's assistant general secretary, said last night:
'This means one-in-six civilian workers in the Ministry of Defence will be
thrown out of a job within the next three years.'
He said that the unions would be calling for an immediate inquiry by the
Commons defence committee into the operational effects of the white paper
proposals and that the Commons public accounts committee should inquire into
the Pounds 1bn a year cost of contracting out work in the MoD.
Mr Ross Burns, secretary to the industrial trade unions at Devonport, said
the latest job losses at Royal Navy stores depots in Devon were 'a dirty
trick to pull on people who have given damned loyal service to the
government and to the country'.
