<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Retailers win supply rights for newspapers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Independent retailers have won greater access to supplies of newspapers from
wholesalers after a lengthy debate about the newspaper distribution
industry.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission found last December that newspaper
wholesalers operated a complex monopoly and that some practices - refusing
supplies in an area they judged to be adequately served - operated against
the public interest. There was, however, a fear among existing newsagents
that a sudden increase in new outlets might disrupt the distribution network
and undermine the sale-or-return system and home delivery of newspapers.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said yesterday that subject to
satisfactory undertakings he had decided to accept a new industry code of
practice, rather than introducing a statutory order prohibiting practices
found to be against the public interest, as he had warned.
The code, put forward by the Association of Newspaper and Magazine
Wholesalers, will define conditions under which a new retailer will have a
right of access to newspaper supplies.
Established retailers will be able to sub-retail or transfer copies within
500 metres from their outlets in urban areas and 1km in other areas. New
retailers will have to meet a minimum weekly order of 50 per cent of average
orders for the area and pay a returnable deposit equal to three weeks'
supplies.
There will be a right of appeal in the case of disputes to a new body to be
set up under the code.
Mr John Gardner, managing director of VG, the convenience store group which
led a campaign for greater access to newspaper supplies, yesterday welcomed
the outcome.
He said: 'Independent grocers will now be able to offer newspapers to their
customers. For decades now newsagents have been able to sell groceries, but
grocers were denied the right to sell newspapers. These unfair practices
have now been abolished.'
The minister has asked Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading,
to negotiate satisfactory undertakings from the wholesalers that they will
keep to the terms of the code of practice.
</TEXT>
