<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Income figures inflame poverty row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Controversy over the extent of poverty in the UK was renewed yesterday by
government figures showing that the real incomes of the bottom 10 per cent
of the population have fallen by 17 per cent since 1979.
This maintains a continuing pattern of decline in the income of the bottom
group after housing costs. It fell 14 per cent between 1979 and 1990-91, and
was 17 per cent lower by 1991-92. Before housing costs are taken into
account the real income of the bottom 10 per cent is unchanged since 1979.
The figures were published in the government's Households Below Average
Incomes statistical analysis.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, said that the results 'do not
show that the poor have become poorer'. He said spending patterns in the
bottom 10 per cent of income distribution suggested that the income figures
did not reflect true living standards.
The pressure group Church Action on Poverty said poverty had reached
scandalous levels. It said: 'Poverty is not an incurable disease. Yet still
we have no indication of regret or remorse from the government, nor any
signs of a plan to reconnect those who are systematically cut adrift from
mainstream society.'
The Child Poverty Action Group said that Britain should be 'deeply ashamed'
by the problems revealed in the report.
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, said: 'It is not a fringe
that is excluded from increased prosperity, but a great mass of ordinary
decent working people.'
The government says that the figures reflect factors such as the increase in
unemployment during the recession rather than a growth in absolute poverty.
However, the report provides further evidence of growing disparity in
incomes between the top and bottom groups. The 17 per cent decline in income
of the bottom group since 1979 compares with a 36 per cent average increase
for the population as a whole, and a 62 per cent rise after housing costs
for the wealthiest 10 per cent.
Anti-poverty campaigners say this shows the UK is developing into a US-style
society with a widening gap between its richest and poorest.
In 1979 the proportion of the population receiving less than half average
income was 8 per cent before housing costs and 9 per cent after. These
proportions rose to 21 per cent and 25 per cent by 1991-92.
</TEXT>
