<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Radical council shake-up proposed for East Anglia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
East Anglian local government should be radically reorganised with eight new
unitary authorities replacing Norfolk and Suffolk county councils and the
area's 14 district councils, the Local Government Commission said yesterday.
Under the proposals, Norwich and Ipswich would become self-governing cities.
Total costs could be as high as Pounds 37m, according to the commission,
while the annual savings might be as little as Pounds 1m.
King's Lynn and West Norfolk District Council would become a unitary
authority within its existing boundaries. There would be five mergers: Great
Yarmouth in Norfolk with Waveney in Suffolk; North Norfolk and Broadland
councils; Breckland with South Norfolk; Forest Heath, St Edmudsbury and the
western parts of Mid Suffolk and Babergh would become West Suffolk; and
Suffolk Coastal with the eastern parts of Mid Suffolk and Babergh would form
East Suffolk.
The commission believes the only viable alternative to this ambitious system
would be to leave the structure unchanged, with Norwich and Ipswich
remaining as district councils within larger counties.
The commission believes that the second option is supported by 'the majority
of local town and parish councils'.
The total number of mainland county councils which the commission has
recommended for abolition so far is 22. However, in 13 cases it has also
suggested the two-tier system as an alternative.
All households in the counties concerned have been sent leaflets in a
consultation exercise which will continue until September. If this reveals
support for the two-tier system, the commission could rule out
reorganisation.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, who is a Suffolk MP, has said he
supports unitary councils because they allow greater accountability, and has
already asked the commission to review again three counties where it has
recommended keeping the two-tier system.
</TEXT>
