<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / M and S decides to open on Sundays
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Marks and Spencer, and the John Lewis Partnership, two of the stalwarts in
the campaign against seven-day-a-week trading, yesterday announced their
plans to open on Sunday.
The new Sunday trading law, which comes into effect at the end of next
month, means that shops will be allowed to open legally for at least six
hours on a Sunday. Current restrictions are widely flouted, with about
145,000 shops ignoring the 1950 Shops Act.
Sir Richard Greenbury, chairman of M and S, told the company's annual
general meeting yesterday: 'There are clearly a number of places where all
the neighbouring retailers will now open on Sunday, and in order to satisfy
customer needs, and protect our share of the market, we will open in those
locations.'
M and S would open 'most, if not all' of its stores on Sundays throughout
the December Christmas trading period and, beyond that, would 'continue to
evaluate the situation', he said.
Separately, the John Lewis Partnership said it would open 19 of its 108
Waitrose supermarket branches on Sundays from September 4. The current
illegal Sunday opening by competitors was costing the company Pounds 1m a
week, it said.
John Lewis was originally part of the Keep Sunday Special Campaign, which
was also backed by the main churches, while M and S was active in the
Retailers for Shops Act Reform. The two groups joined forces in November
last year in a failed attempt to limit deregulation in England and Wales -
Scotland is already fully deregulated. A campaigner against Sunday trading
yesterday won the right to bring private prosecutions against superstores
that open on Sundays.
Two High Court judges ruled that Mr Roy Edey was entitled to launch such
actions after Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, declined to
intervene.
However, Lord Justice Butler Sloss and Mr Justice Macpherson added that, in
view of changes in the law, magistrates 'may not regard the offences
disclosed as being particularly serious'.
AGM report, Page 19
