<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / 20% of directors take pay cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One in five directors in some of the UK's biggest companies took a pay cut
last year, according to a report by Korn/Ferry Carre/Orban International,
the recruitment consultants.
The report surveyed salaries of more than 1,000 senior executives, in 154 of
the UK's largest companies.
It found that two in five top executives received less than a 2 per cent
increase in their total cash earnings. 'This firmly contradicts the public
perception that senior managers are paid inflated salaries,' said Mr Michael
Brandon, the Korn/Ferry director who co-wrote the report.
But the findings also revealed broad discrepancies in the upper and lower
earnings of managers. While 40 per cent of those in the survey had
relatively low increases, another 15 per cent had annual increases of more
than 30 per cent. More than 40 per cent received increases above 10 per
cent.
The report said that those earning the highest salaries were generally
obtaining proportionally greater increases.
The median increase in cash earnings of all the directors of 8.4 per cent
was largely due to increased bonuses, said the report. Basic salaries on
average rose slightly ahead of inflation, by 4 to 5 per cent.
Mr Brandon said: 'What we are finding is that while there is a whole group
of people doing very well there is another group of directors out there who
are not.' Building Societies and mutual life offices are losing out in
competition with the quoted banks and insurance companies to attract the
highest quality directors, a report says today.
The Incomes Data Services management pay review compares the pay packages of
top directors in the 11 largest building societies and 11 mutual life
offices with those of equivalent directors in quoted banks and insurances.
The IDS report said that the societies were confronting the problem by
adopting long-term bonus schemes linked to various measures such as sales
achievements and cost controls.
Report published by IDS, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS, Tel 071
2503434
