<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / MMC to probe advertising bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission is to investigate a bid by More
O'Ferrall, the poster advertising company, for London Transport Advertising,
the London Transport subsidiary which is being privatised.
More O'Ferrall, one of four bidders for LTA, said it was 'extremely
disappointed' about the referral. The resulting delay could jeopardise its
chances of a successful bid.
LTA generates about Pounds 23m a year from the sale of poster space in
Underground stations and on buses and trains. It employs about 300 people.
It had been expected that the sale would be completed by the end of this
month but the government has now given the MMC a deadline of mid-October to
present its report.
Mr Vincent Slevin, More O'Ferrall UK managing director, said it was up to
London Transport to evaluate the bids and take the MMC investigation into
account.
The Department of Trade and Industry is concerned that More O'Ferrall's bid
'raises competition concerns in the poster advertising market in the London
area which merit investigation by the MMC'.
If More O'Ferrall were to be successful it would control about 21 per cent
of the UK outdoor advertising market and about 38 per cent of the market in
London. A market share of 25 per cent commonly triggers an MMC
investigation.
Mr Slevin said the company had hoped that the bid would not be referred
because the media world was changing. Carlton had 55 per cent of the London
television market and Capital Radio 65 per cent of London radio, he added.
The three other bidders for LTA are a management and employee buy-out; a
joint bid by Giraudy, a French poster company, and Primesight, a UK outdoor
company; and a consortium led by Transportation Displays, a US transport
advertising company.
More O'Ferrall shares closed down 1p at 361p.
</TEXT>
