<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Building optimism marred
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Doubts about the strength of the housing market recovery are clouding an
otherwise positive picture of improving prospects for the construction
industry, the latest quarterly survey from the Building Employers
Confederation shows.
The survey, published yesterday, raises concerns about employment in the
industry, with evidence of emerging skills shortages, in spite of the large
number of job losses in the recession.
The report shows increasing confidence of growth in the next year among a
rising number of companies. A significant proportion of companies expect to
employ more people over the next few months.
It also indicates an upturn in the level of construction activity in the
second quarter of this year, with more companies working at a higher level
of capacity than in the first quarter. More than one-third of companies
reported increased output in the second quarter  - the highest proportion
since the second quarter of 1989.
The upward trend of inquiries about new work was confined almost entirely to
the private sector, however, as public sector inquiries for new schools and
hospitals fell in comparison with the first three months of this year.
Sir Brian Hill, BEC president, said: 'If the present uncertainties in the
housing market reflect consumer confidence in the economy as a whole, this
is indeed worrying.'
He expressed concern about shortages of skilled workers, particularly
bricklayers and carpenters. 'We have a major task ahead of us in stepping up
training and also attracting back into our industry some of the many skilled
people who have left it,' he said.
