<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Regulator's plans may restrict Railtrack profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tough curbs could be imposed on the profits of Railtrack, the company which
has taken over British Rail's track and signalling, if proposals unveiled
yesterday by the rail industry regulator are put into effect.
Mr John Swift QC, the rail regulator, suggests in an assessment of the
proposed access agreements to be signed between Railtrack and the train
operating companies, that commercial pressures could require Railtrack to
reduce the value of its assets and the level of return it made on them.
He says: 'The combined effect might be to impose a significant reduction in
Railtrack's profitability post-privatisation.'
The tone of his 50-page paper suggests that Mr Swift will adopt a rigorous
approach to Railtrack's efficiency and profitability. Its detail indicates
the extent to which many practical issues involved in rail privatisation
have still to be solved.
Mr Swift questions whether the 8 per cent return on assets set for Railtrack
by the Treasury is sustainable, because private-sector returns have fallen
in recent years.
He suggests that valuing Railtrack's assets on the basis of what it would
cost to replace them may not be realistic and that their value would be set
much lower in the commercial market place when the company is privatised.
Mr Swift is seeking comments on the document, and on a second paper which
looks at the question of increasing competition on the railway, by the
middle of August.
He plans to publish policy statements in November and April. Once agreed, a
formula would apply for five years.
Railtrack did not comment yesterday on the detail of the proposals but
welcomed the start of the consultation process and the news that agreements
would last for five years.
Mr Swift said it was not the intention of his proposals to make Railtrack
more difficult to float on the stock market. But he wanted to resolve the
regulatory issues before the privatisation of BR was completed rather than
waiting until afterwards as had happened with the water and gas industries.
The consultation document says that in the early years Railtrack will have
an incentive to improve its operating efficiency as its required return
rises from 5.1 per cent to 8 per cent, but after that incentives related to
the retail prices index may be needed. The company would be required to hold
cost increases to a percentage figure below the retail prices index.
The regulator will also want to see that the figure which Railtrack charges
to depreciation in its accounts relates to actual spending on track and
station replacement. He will also look for efficiency improvements in
infrastructure maintenance.
In a second document on the subject of competition Mr Swift says that he
expects exclusive rights to run trains on a particular stretch of track to
be granted only in exceptional cases and for limited periods.
The government is keen to open the rail tracks to independent train
companies operating alongside the franchised companies but this could make
the franchises less attractive.
Framework for the Approval of Railtrack's Access Charges and Competition for
Railway Passenger Services. Office of Rail Regulator, 1 Waterhouse Square,
Holborn Bars, 138-142 Holborn, London EC1N 2SU.
</TEXT>
