<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Business predicts increase in staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Businesses plan to hire more staff in the three months to the end of
September in spite of expectations that new orders will grow at a slower
rate, the latest quarterly survey from Dun &amp; Bradstreet, the business
information group, shows.
The company's poll of 1,500 managing directors found that 40 per cent
expected to increase staffing levels in the current three months compared
with a year ago, with 11 per cent planning a reduction. The balance - a
positive 29 percentage points - was slightly up from the second quarter and
the highest for five years. Nearly half the service companies polled plan to
increase staff.
The survey found that the balance of companies expecting increased net
profits and selling prices rose slightly between the second and third
quarters, while expectations of net sales, exports and inventory levels fell
marginally.
The positive balance expecting new orders to rise in the latest quarter
compared with a year ago fell to 45 percentage points from 56 points in the
second.
Dun &amp; Bradstreet said that the survey highlighted the fragility of Britain's
economic recovery. This was disputed by the Treasury, which said that the
fall in orders growth could reflect a seasonal pattern.
Past surveys show that the balance of new orders has deteriorated between
the second and third quarters of every year since 1989. The latest poll
found that just over half of businesses expected to increase orders in this
quarter compared with a year ago, while 42 per cent expected no change.
The north-west and west Midlands appeared to be the most confident regions.
</TEXT>
