<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Electricity liberalisation plea rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity industry regulator, yesterday
angered large electricity users by turning down proposals to liberalise the
electricity market.
He said that no case had been made for significant changes to the rules for
the pool, the wholesale market for electricity, which have been blamed for
pushing up prices.
The pool arrangements 'have worked well', he said in a long-awaited report,
and claims that security of supply would be threatened and competition would
not work 'have been proved wrong'.
In particular, Prof Littlechild said there was no case for allowing
generators and consumers to bypass the pool and trade directly with each
other. Under current rules large generators are obliged to sell all their
output through the pool.
Intensive energy users, which have criticised the sharp rise in electricity
prices, have been pressing for liberalisation of pool trading.
Earlier this week the Chemical Industries Association put outside-pool
trading forward as a means of increasing competition among generators.
Mr Doug Roger, one of the association's executive directors, said yesterday
that he was 'amazed' that the regulator should have turned the proposal
down.
However, Mr Peter Rost of the Major Energy Users Association said that while
some big industries would be disappointed, smaller companies would welcome
the news because they lacked sufficient bargaining power to strike
one-to-one deals directly with the generators.
Prof Littlechild said there was little tangible evidence of the likely gains
that trading outside the pool could bring, and it would be costly to make
the necessary arrangements. It might also damage volume and transparency in
the pool, which would place smaller competitors and new entrants at a
disadvantage.
But he said he wanted further improvements to the pool, although his
research had shown opposition to a suggestion that generators should be paid
their bid prices. At present generators receive the price bid by the most
expensive plant needed to satisfy demand at a particular time of day,
regardless of what they bid themselves.
The regulator's views were laid out in a report produced in response to a
request last year from Mr Tim Eggar, the energy minister. In parallel with
his inquiry the pool management has been preparing its own recommendations,
which will be put forward later this year.
London Docklands Development Corporation is inviting 16 companies to bid to
participate in a project to supply heat and power to the Royal Docks. The
project would supply power directly, bypassing the local electricity
company.
Trading outside the Pool. Offer, Hagley House, Hagley Road, Edgbaston,
Birmingham B16 8QG. Tel (021) 456 2100.
</TEXT>
