FT  15 JUL 94 / BCCI creditors attack liquidator
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two members of the creditors' committee to the collapsed Bank of Credit and
Commerce International yesterday renewed their attack on the liquidators
from accountants Touche Ross.
In a newsletter due to be circulated to members today, Dr Adil Elias and Mr
Tony Scott of the BCCI Depositors' Protection Association questioned whether
the liquidators had acted 'in the most effective and cost-efficient way'.
They said the liquidators' costs had 'always been too high'.
They said they remained 'wholly unconvinced' that the new agreement
negotiated between the liquidators and the government of Abu Dhabi, majority
shareholder in the bank, was the best settlement that could be achieved.
The newsletter accused Touche Ross of taking a 'high-handed approach' which
had imposed strategies on the creditors - seeking only their ratification
rather than their advice. The men were 'unhappy' and still negotiating with
the liquidators over the requirement for confidentiality covering the
creditors' committee meetings, which meant they could not pass information
on to depositors.
They question the assiduousness with which Touche Ross is pursuing its claim
against the Bank of England, which was sued for alleged negligence in its
role as supervisor to BCCI.
