<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Street-digging code aims to save trees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A national code of conduct on the way streets are dug up is to be launched
this autumn by the power, gas, water and telecommunications industries to
try to protect thousands of endangered trees.
Environmentalists and local authorities are concerned about serious damage
to trees caused particularly by cable television companies digging up
pavements and severing roots.
Professor Chris Baines, an environmental consultant who is leading a
campaign to protect street trees, told a conference in Norwich yesterday
that few trees would be left within a few years because cable companies were
licensed to dig 60,000 miles of trenches by the year 2000.
He called for a change in the law which excludes utilities and cable
companies from local authority planning controls when digging up streets.
He said: 'Trees provide the air-conditioning for our towns and cities. It is
criminal to destroy them when we are becoming increasingly worried about the
effects of traffic pollution.'
He said trenches dug by cable companies and utilities severed roots which
provided water, oxygen and anchorage. Almost all these roots lay close to
the surface.
Draft rules for a voluntary code of conduct have been prepared for the
Arboricultural Association and the National Joint Utilities Group
representing all leading utilities.
The working party which devised the rules was chaired by the Department of
the Environment and included the Cable Television Association and local
authority tree officers.
It is hoped that all local authorities will adopt the code, which is
expected to call for the use of small-bore tunnelling close to trees
wherever possible. It says trenches near trees should be hand-dug to protect
roots if tunnelling is impossible, arguing that the increased cost is likely
to be small compared with the total installation bill.
Repair and maintenance techniques which do not require pavements to be
excavated will be encouraged.
Designers and planners will be asked to keep services at a safe distance
from mature trees in new developments.
</TEXT>
