<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Alliance enters overdraft rate war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Alliance &amp; Leicester building society, the UK's fourth largest, yesterday
became the latest high street financial organisation to cut its overdraft
rate in a ploy to attract new customers.
Alliance &amp; Leicester's new rate for an authorised overdraft in its Alliance
account is 9.5 per cent equivalent annual rate.
The rate reduction, made only two weeks after the account was launched, is
seen as a sign of how quickly the battle to win personal customers is
intensifying.
The current round of rate-cutting was started by Abbey National bank, the
former building society, at the end of last month when it reduced the annual
percentage rate on authorised overdrafts to 9.9 per cent.
Although this sparked fears of a price war, the largest high street banks,
which have most of the estimated 33m personal current accounts, have
dismissed the move and have expressed doubt that the reductions will be
maintained.
However, Nationwide, the second-largest society, and Woolwich, the third
largest, have announced substantial reductions in their authorised overdraft
rates.
Alliance &amp; Leicester said that it would probably reduce the overdraft rate
on its Giro account.
The society sees the Giro account as comparable with bank current accounts,
while the Alliance account competes with other building society current
accounts.
Mr John Wriglesworth, societies analyst at UBS, said that cutting overdraft
rates represented another, and relatively cheap way for societies to attract
retail deposits.
Although societies recorded net inflows of retail funds in April and May,
the net outflow in the first quarter totalled Pounds 1.3bn.
</TEXT>
