<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Multinational police force in line for Haiti
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES and JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The White House yesterday announced that up to 12 nations had agreed to join
a US-led force to police Haiti in the event of ousted president
Jean-Bertrand Aristide being restored to power.
Indications of growing consensus on Haiti came as Mr Aristide demanded that
the international community take 'swift and definitive' action to remove the
republic's current military leadership.
Although he added that he was constitutionally prohibited from calling for
military intervention - a stance which has previously been seen as a
stumbling block to multilateral military action - his statement appeared to
be a veiled endorsement of a US invasion. President Bill Clinton has
repeatedly said that military intervention is an option in attempts to
restore democracy.
Ms Madeleine Albright, US ambassador to the United Nations, said that
Argentina, Chile, Brazil, Barbados, Jamaica, Trinidad, Guyana, Suriname,
Belize, El Salvador and Honduras had agreed to participate in a multilateral
force.
According to Caribbean officials, in a series of meetings last week, Mr
William Gray, the US adviser on Haiti, and senior representatives of the US
National Security Council, the Defence Department and the US army, told
Caribbean leaders that the US would invade Haiti if the military regime had
not imploded within three weeks.
The Americans had said that the US would only take this course of action if
the United Nations Security Council judged it necessary
However, the US was 'alarmed' at the increase in refugees from Haiti over
the previous fortnight and had told Caribbean leaders that it felt the only
way to end the flow of boat people was to force the military to leave
office.
The US was willing to play a prominent role in a multilateral operation to
that end, Caribbean officials said.
However, congressional and administration officials in the US yesterday
insisted that only US forces would be used in the initial phases of an
invasion. The US military could later be reinforced and replaced by a
multinational peacekeeping team, US officials said.
Caribbean leaders confirmed that the US government wanted them, as Haiti's
neighbours, to contribute to an international military and police force,
which would maintain security and public order in the early days after Mr
Aristide's return.
Mr Christopher Thomas, acting secretary general of the Organisation of
American States, said in Washington that the OAS had been discussing a
multilateral 'reconstruction effort' that could include peacekeeping troops
which would move in after Mr Aristide's return.
Meanwhile, senior administration and Pentagon officials said that US forces
had rehearsed an emergency evacuation of civilians on the island of Great
Inagua, in the Bahamas, on Wednesday.
The operation was similar to the operation that would be used to rescue US
or other citizens from Haiti, they said.
The 400 US Marines who carried out the exercise are part of a force now
numbering 2,800, which is positioned off Haiti's coast.
Their mission is to evacuate the 5,000 US nationals in Haiti should their
lives be in danger.
The White House also expressed alarm yesterday over deteriorating human
rights conditions in Haiti.
As UN human rights observers left Haiti under orders from Lt Gen Raoul
Cedras, Haiti's de facto ruler, officials from the US embassy in Haiti were
investigating the deaths of 12 Haitian men whose bodies were found near the
Haitian capital, Port-au-Prince.
The US state department issued a strong rebuke to the Haitian regime over
the killings.
</TEXT>
