<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / Retail sales increase by 0.6% in June
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US retail sales increased 0.6 per cent between May and June after falling
for two consecutive months, the Commerce Department said yesterday.
The report follows other recent signs of renewed economic vigour, including
a 379,000 rise in non-farm payroll employment in June - far above Wall
Street projections.
The recovery in retail sales mainly reflected higher sales of motor
vehicles, which rose 1.5 per cent from May. Other strong sectors included
building materials, up 2.7 per cent, and department stores, up 1.8 per cent.
Overall, retail sales are running 6.6 per cent higher than in June last
year, before allowing for inflation of about 2.5 per cent.
Officials released revised figures for May showing a decline of 0.4 per cent
rather than 0.2 per cent as initially reported. Allowing for the weakness of
sales in April and May, analysts expect real consumer spending to grow at an
annual rate of little more than 1 per cent in the second quarter, sharply
down from 5.2 per cent in the first three months.
But strong growth in capital spending, a rebound in construction and a
rebuilding in corporate inventories are expected to compensate for weaker
consumer spending.
Most forecasters expect real economic growth at an annual rate of at least
3.5 per cent in the second quarter, and possibly significantly faster,
against 3 per cent in the first quarter.
