<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JUL 94 / World Trade News: China to import top-class films
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From OUR BEIJING CORRESPONDENT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
China yesterday said it would allow its cinemas to screen newly-made foreign
films and to share profits with producers, but only about 10 'excellent' new
movies would be signed for screening each year.
'An end is in sight to the 40-year-old tradition of buying out-dated and
low-grade but cheap foreign movies,' said Chinafilm, the state monopoly film
importer.
'We are negotiating with world-renowned film corporations in the US and some
other countries, with which we had no contact before,' said China-film
spokesman Mr Wang Zengfu. He declined to identify the companies or the
profit-sharing arrangements.
The imports might include Oscar winners and other leading films, according
to the official Xinhua news service.
Mr Wang said the selected films for screening would 'reflect world
civilisation and modern achievements in film and art techniques'.
Up to now, Chinese television and cinemas have recycled classic films such
as The Sound of Music, Gone with the Wind and Roman Holiday. TV has often
shown soap operas, including Dynasty, and Beauty and the Beast.
After the 1989 crackdown on dissent culminated in the Tiananmen massacre,
cinemas were compelled to run communist propaganda films and were nearly
always empty apart from young couples using their free tickets as an
opportunity to cuddle in the dark.
In 1991, Politburo Standing Committee member Li Ruihuan, a relatively
liberal senior leader, reversed the restrictions on films with no propaganda
value, and cinema managers looked forward to getting out of the red.
But China's film makers still have running battles with the censors and with
bureaucrats at state-owned movie studios. This has caused a shortage of
box-office hits, so that most of the country's 200,000 cinemas are still
losing money.
Many Chinese prefer to stay at home and watch one of the new rash of locally
made soaps or pirate videos. Most of the latter are dubbed or produced in
Taiwan and Hong Kong and many are lewd and violent, despite repeated police
crackdowns on both pornography and pirating.
In the past two years, foreign film makers undertaking joint productions in
China have had frequent clashes with censors. There are so many taboos that
it is hard to predict what kind of international hits might be allowed into
the country. Earlier this month China said it would impose new censorship
rules on imported films.
'The plan is aimed at expanding cultural exchanges, reviving the film
market, meeting the audience's needs and developing the national film
industry,' Mr Wang said.
Xinhua said western films were introduced in the 1960s but 'most of the
movies were second-rate or third-rate, usually seven or eight years old'.
</TEXT>
